Adversarial Training in Machine Learning for Domain Adaptation

Little research has been done in using adversarial learning to do domain adaptation for MT system.
A good starting point is:

Britz, Denny, Quoc Le, and Reid Pryzant. "Effective domain mixing for neural machine translation." Proceedings of the Second Conference on Machine Translation. 2017.

This paper consider the problem of training NMT over two domains. However, simply mixing the data can degrade the performance. This paper suggest using multitask learning to improve the performance. Specifically, the model is jointly trained with a classification task to identify which domain the data comes from.

Discriminative mixing model and target-side token mixing model outperform simply mixing the data. However the adversarial model is worse than the discriminative model. The adversarial training is wrong in this paper, because the adversarial part encourages the encoder to give similar encoding for two domains.

Other Domain Adaptation Methods

Data Selection

Numerous research has been donw in data selection for NMT and SMT.
[1] and [2] select LM training data with (cross entropy difference) CED according to an in-domain LM and a generic LM. Recently, [3] emploies a neural-network version of it along with a dynamic data selection idea. [4] and [5] build classifiers to select data based on a trusted data.

Generate Pseudo-Parallel Sentences

When there are not enough parallel corpora, there are also studies that generate pseudo-parallel sentences. [6] finds pseudo-parallel sentences based on sentence embeddings.

Instant Weighting

For example, [7] focuses on instance weighting for NMT to solve the problem of domain adaptation.

Fine tuning

Fine tuning is the conventional way for domain adaptation. In summary, an NMT system on a resource rich out-of-domain corpus is trained until convergence, and then its parameters are fine tuned on a resource poor in-domain corpus. Several methods have been purposed to address overfitting problem in fine tuning, such as, mixed fine tuning and regularization. For details, see section 4.2.1 in [8].

Taking Domain as Input Feature

For example, [9] uses clustering to discover domains, and then treat domain as an input feature or a tag.

Other References

Denoising Neural Machine Translation Training with Trusted Data and Online Data Selection propose to apply data selection method in denoising MT training.
Adversarial Neural Machine Translation propose to use GAN to train MT system.
[Adversarial Multi-Criteria Learning for Chinese Word Segmentation] incorporate adversarial learning into other NLP tasks.
A Survey of Domain Adaptation for Neural Machine Translation is a comprehensive survey.
